DFS goes as deep as possible first, then backtracks.


1.Create result list
 To store DFS traversal.
2.Create visited array
 To avoid revisiting nodes.
3.Create Stack (LIFO)
DFS always uses Stack (explicitly or via recursion).
Push starting node (0)
4.While stack is not empty
5.Pop top node
  If not visited:
  Mark visited
6.Add to result
7.Push all its neighbours (in reverse order)

class Solution {
    public ArrayList<Integer> dfs(ArrayList<ArrayList<Integer>> adj) {
        ArrayList<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();
        boolean[] visited = new boolean[adj.size()];
        Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

        // start DFS from node 0
        stack.push(0);

        while (!stack.isEmpty()) {
            int node = stack.pop();

            if (!visited[node]) {
                visited[node] = true;
                result.add(node);

                // push neighbors (in reverse order for correct traversal)
                for (int i = adj.get(node).size() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
                    int neighbor = adj.get(node).get(i);
                    if (!visited[neighbor]) {
                        stack.push(neighbor);
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
}
